an unprecedented scale and has brought concerns about refugees into sharp focus. There are forty million refugees in the world—1 in 130 inhabitants of this planet. In this first interdisciplinary study of the issue, fifteen scholars from diverse fields focus on the worldwide disruption of "trust" as a sentiment, a concept, and an experience.Contributors provide a rich array of essays that maintain a delicate balance between providing specific details of the refugee experience and exploring corresponding theories of trust and mistrust. Their subjects range widely across the globe, and include Palestinians, Cambodians, Tamils, and Mayan Indians of Guatemala. By examining what individuals experience when removed from their own culture, these essays reflect on individual identity and culture as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a20th century world politics.  aabuse of trust.  acambodia.  acultural studies.  acyprus.  ademographic studies.  adisplaced people.  adisplacement.  aethnography.  agermany.  agreece.  aguatemala.  ahumanitarian.  aindividual identity.  ainterdisciplinary.  amayan indians.  amemory.  anative peoples.  apalestine.  apublic policy.  arefuge.  arefugee experience.  arefugee film.  arefugee narratives.  arefugee women.  arefugees.  asocial services.  asocial welfare.  atamil.  atorture.  atrust and mistrust.  atrust.  aworldwide disruption.1 aAleinikoff, T. Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, E. Valentine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, E. Valentine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer, Michael M.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo